---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'FAQ | classactionsettlementcalc.com';
const description = 'Frequently asked questions about class action settlements: how to file a claim, timeline, attorney fees, and opting out.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
  <h2>Do I have to do anything to receive my settlement share?</h2>
  <p>Usually yes &mdash; you must submit a claim form by the claims deadline. Class members who do nothing typically receive nothing (though in some small-claims cases, the court may order automatic distribution to avoid the cost of a claims process).</p>
  <h2>How long does it take to receive payment?</h2>
  <p>After final court approval, expect 6&ndash;18 months for distribution. The timeline depends on appeals, claims processing time, and administrative complexity. Large consumer settlements can take 2&ndash;3 years from filing to check.</p>
  <h2>Can I opt out and sue on my own?</h2>
  <p>Yes. Class members have the right to opt out during the exclusion period specified in the class notice. Opting out preserves your right to sue individually. This makes sense only if your individual claim is large enough to justify litigation costs.</p>
  <h2>How much do class action attorneys take?</h2>
  <p>In federal court, attorneys typically receive 25&ndash;33% of the fund (the &ldquo;common fund&rdquo; doctrine). Courts scrutinize fee requests; in large megafund cases, fees may be limited to 10&ndash;15%. The fee is paid from the settlement, not in addition to it.</p>
  <h2>What is a cy pres distribution?</h2>
  <p>When individual payments are too small to process economically (e.g., $0.50 per class member), courts may direct unclaimed or residual funds to charities or nonprofit organizations with a nexus to the class&rsquo;s injury.</p>
  <h2>What if the settlement is a coupon settlement?</h2>
  <p>Coupon settlements provide class members with vouchers or discounts rather than cash. The Class Action Fairness Act (CAFA) requires courts to scrutinize coupon settlements and limits attorney fees to a percentage of coupons actually redeemed.</p>
  <h2>Is my settlement taxable?</h2>
  <p>It depends on the underlying claim. Recoveries for physical injury or illness are generally not taxable. Payments for economic loss, statutory damages, or emotional distress may be taxable. Consult a tax professional for your specific situation.</p>
</BaseLayout>
